Flowers of most members of Sapindales are nectariferous and often have a conspicuous nectary (
 Kubitzki 2011; 
 Ronse De Craene and Haston 2006). However, out of the nine families and ca. 6550 species (
 Stevens 2001 onwards), osmophores have only been reported and studied in two genera of Rutaceae (
 Bussel 
  et al. 1995
 ; 
 Marques 
  et al. 2015
 ), while those reported in two species of a genus of Sapindaceae were not studied in detail and lacked chemical characterization of their volatile compounds (
 Lima 
  et al. 2016
 ).
